WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.002 --> 00:00:01.710
CHELSEA SEABRON: Good
evening, everybody.

00:00:01.710 --> 00:00:03.341
And welcome to Google New York.

00:00:03.341 --> 00:00:04.590
It's so great to see you guys.

00:00:04.590 --> 00:00:06.340
We've been preparing
for you for weeks,

00:00:06.340 --> 00:00:09.190
so it's awesome to
see you guys here.

00:00:09.190 --> 00:00:11.720
My name is Chelsea Seabron,
and it is my pleasure

00:00:11.720 --> 00:00:15.410
to welcome you on behalf
of google.org who's

00:00:15.410 --> 00:00:18.820
sponsoring this along with our
amazing partners to my left

00:00:18.820 --> 00:00:22.030
here from HBO,
Participant Media.

00:00:22.030 --> 00:00:25.810
We have some members of the
3 and 1/2 Minutes, 10 Bullets

00:00:25.810 --> 00:00:27.670
film team, as well with us.

00:00:27.670 --> 00:00:31.140
So the culmination of
everybody here today

00:00:31.140 --> 00:00:33.310
is because of
those partnerships.

00:00:33.310 --> 00:00:36.160
So some of you may
be wondering why

00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:38.420
is Google taking on this film?

00:00:38.420 --> 00:00:40.510
Why are we here
talking about this?

00:00:40.510 --> 00:00:44.250
And this journey ultimately
started about six months ago

00:00:44.250 --> 00:00:46.450
through our
partnership with PICO.

00:00:46.450 --> 00:00:49.600
And so, through PICO, we've
had opportunity of expanding

00:00:49.600 --> 00:00:51.487
that relationship to HBO.

00:00:51.487 --> 00:00:53.070
And I would love for
you guys to stand

00:00:53.070 --> 00:00:55.340
just so people can
see who you are

00:00:55.340 --> 00:00:57.090
from HBO, Participant Media.

00:00:57.090 --> 00:00:59.860
We've got Urban Cusp who's
a partnership that has come.

00:00:59.860 --> 00:01:01.484
So let's give them
a round of applause.

00:01:01.484 --> 00:01:04.802
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:08.120 --> 00:01:11.560
So pretty much this
partnership started

00:01:11.560 --> 00:01:14.230
after the unfortunate
and very tragic

00:01:14.230 --> 00:01:16.610
shootings that
happened in Charleston.

00:01:16.610 --> 00:01:18.490
And, after that, that
was the first moment

00:01:18.490 --> 00:01:21.810
as a Google community
that our various employee

00:01:21.810 --> 00:01:25.220
groups came together and
said we have to do something.

00:01:25.220 --> 00:01:27.500
We to come together
in solidarity.

00:01:27.500 --> 00:01:30.490
And we ended up actually doing
a global-wide movement where

00:01:30.490 --> 00:01:32.960
everyone wore "Black
Lives Matter" t-shirts

00:01:32.960 --> 00:01:33.750
across the globe.

00:01:33.750 --> 00:01:36.450
And we were posting
these via Google+.

00:01:36.450 --> 00:01:40.160
And it was a beautiful day
where, for the first time,

00:01:40.160 --> 00:01:43.090
we acknowledged what's going
on in our communities that

00:01:43.090 --> 00:01:46.720
ultimately are affecting
each individual employee.

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:51.050
And so, after that
day, google.org

00:01:51.050 --> 00:01:54.310
stepped up in a really huge
way and made a $5 million

00:01:54.310 --> 00:01:56.720
investment in racial justice.

00:01:56.720 --> 00:01:59.740
So this is part of
that investment.

00:01:59.740 --> 00:02:03.170
Since then, we've invested
half of that money

00:02:03.170 --> 00:02:06.440
to organizations in the
Bay Area where I'm from.

00:02:06.440 --> 00:02:09.289
And tonight you
guys are actually

00:02:09.289 --> 00:02:12.120
the first to hear that the
last of that 2 and 1/2 million

00:02:12.120 --> 00:02:13.770
will go out any day now.

00:02:13.770 --> 00:02:15.340
So let's give it
up for google.org.

00:02:15.340 --> 00:02:17.725
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:21.550 --> 00:02:23.810
So my colleagues are back home.

00:02:23.810 --> 00:02:26.510
They send their regards from
California, Justin Steele

00:02:26.510 --> 00:02:28.922
and Jacquelline Fuller,
from google.org.

00:02:28.922 --> 00:02:30.630
And, thought they're
not physically here,

00:02:30.630 --> 00:02:33.970
they're trying to get
those grants out the door.

00:02:33.970 --> 00:02:37.720
So let's talk a little bit
about tonight's program.

00:02:37.720 --> 00:02:40.500
And, as you can see, we've
got food and networking.

00:02:40.500 --> 00:02:43.910
Hopefully you've met somebody
who doesn't look like you.

00:02:43.910 --> 00:02:47.330
And tonight we really
are challenging everybody

00:02:47.330 --> 00:02:49.700
to get a little uncomfortable.

00:02:49.700 --> 00:02:51.420
And we salute
everybody in this room

00:02:51.420 --> 00:02:56.120
because to take on the choice to
come here tonight was not easy.

00:02:56.120 --> 00:02:58.140
Talking about race is not easy.

00:02:58.140 --> 00:03:00.470
And so, you know, I
salute everybody here

00:03:00.470 --> 00:03:08.730
for taking that decision
to be uncomfortable,

00:03:08.730 --> 00:03:11.390
especially the topic
of tonight's film.

00:03:11.390 --> 00:03:15.300
We have a lot of employees
who have felt their blackness.

00:03:15.300 --> 00:03:17.630
And black and brown
men, especially,

00:03:17.630 --> 00:03:21.310
have been stigmatized with
awful feelings or associations

00:03:21.310 --> 00:03:23.524
of being violent or dangerous.

00:03:23.524 --> 00:03:24.940
And so tonight,
through this film,

00:03:24.940 --> 00:03:27.510
we will explore this topic.

00:03:27.510 --> 00:03:29.660
And I just want you guys
to understand and own

00:03:29.660 --> 00:03:33.170
that we all have bias,
whether it's about race,

00:03:33.170 --> 00:03:34.990
or religion, or anything else.

00:03:34.990 --> 00:03:36.460
We all carry our own bias.

00:03:36.460 --> 00:03:38.330
And so tonight we
just challenge you

00:03:38.330 --> 00:03:42.700
to be uncomfortable, to own the
work we need to do within each

00:03:42.700 --> 00:03:44.260
and every one of us.

00:03:44.260 --> 00:03:47.430
And this is the first step
for you guys, just showing up.

00:03:47.430 --> 00:03:50.150
So thank you for showing up.

00:03:50.150 --> 00:03:51.090
So without-- oh.

00:03:51.090 --> 00:03:52.010
[APPLAUSE]

00:03:52.010 --> 00:03:52.600
Thanks, Ron.

00:03:52.600 --> 00:03:53.740
[CHUCKLING]

00:03:58.370 --> 00:04:00.350
And so, without
much further ado,

00:04:00.350 --> 00:04:01.660
this is our final screening.

00:04:01.660 --> 00:04:03.440
It's actually a
pretty sad moment

00:04:03.440 --> 00:04:05.420
because I've been
traveling with Ron and Lucy

00:04:05.420 --> 00:04:07.170
across the country.

00:04:07.170 --> 00:04:10.200
Google did one of these in
Charleston, South Carolina.

00:04:10.200 --> 00:04:11.920
We did a second one
in San Francisco

00:04:11.920 --> 00:04:14.500
to an audience of
about 1,400 people.

00:04:14.500 --> 00:04:18.029
And tonight is the final, first
time in New York, at that.

00:04:18.029 --> 00:04:20.170
But it's so beautiful
to see you all here

00:04:20.170 --> 00:04:23.320
because we've been on a
little journey, a big journey.

00:04:23.320 --> 00:04:26.450
And Ron and Lucy have been
on a way longer journey.

00:04:26.450 --> 00:04:30.780
So, to kind of kick off an
understanding of that journey,

00:04:30.780 --> 00:04:32.950
let's welcome to the
stage Rahiel Tesfamariam,

00:04:32.950 --> 00:04:34.870
founder of Urban Cusp--

00:04:34.870 --> 00:04:36.850
[APPLAUSE]

00:04:37.840 --> 00:04:42.550
And if you don't know about
Urban Cusp, you must find out.

00:04:42.550 --> 00:04:46.260
Rahiel has done many things from
the "Not One Dime" campaign,

00:04:46.260 --> 00:04:49.200
which hopefully on Black
Friday, no one shopped.

00:04:49.200 --> 00:04:53.210
But if you did, Rahiel will
tell you why not to next year.

00:04:53.210 --> 00:04:56.160
And, Ron and Lucy, if
you guys would also

00:04:56.160 --> 00:04:58.420
come to the stage and--

00:04:58.420 --> 00:05:01.880
[APPLAUSE]

00:05:01.880 --> 00:05:07.290
So Ron and Lucy are the
parents of Jordan Davis who

00:05:07.290 --> 00:05:11.410
have just so bravely and
boldly relived this story time

00:05:11.410 --> 00:05:15.510
and time again to change the
hearts and minds of audience

00:05:15.510 --> 00:05:17.520
members just like yourselves.

00:05:17.520 --> 00:05:19.580
And so I guarantee
you I've known them

00:05:19.580 --> 00:05:21.820
for about six months now.

00:05:21.820 --> 00:05:23.290
And they feel like family.

00:05:23.290 --> 00:05:25.500
And they have
challenged Googlers

00:05:25.500 --> 00:05:28.150
the first time we met
that change starts

00:05:28.150 --> 00:05:29.800
with each and every one of us.

00:05:29.800 --> 00:05:32.390
And so I took that call very
seriously when they told me

00:05:32.390 --> 00:05:34.090
the first time.

00:05:34.090 --> 00:05:36.180
So I guarantee you you'll
fall in love with them

00:05:36.180 --> 00:05:37.090
by the end of today.

00:05:37.090 --> 00:05:39.700
And I just really
honor their courage

00:05:39.700 --> 00:05:43.830
to tell this story over and
over again, despite that.

00:05:43.830 --> 00:05:46.090
And last, but
certainly not least,

00:05:46.090 --> 00:05:49.480
I want to make a plug for HBO.

00:05:49.480 --> 00:05:52.040
This is our only
post-production screening,

00:05:52.040 --> 00:05:54.430
but we had two
pre-production ones.

00:05:54.430 --> 00:05:56.550
But, really, cool
opportunity to get this word

00:05:56.550 --> 00:05:59.430
out even bigger than tonight
is to spread the word

00:05:59.430 --> 00:06:02.350
and get HBO if
you don't have it.

00:06:02.350 --> 00:06:07.000
And you can watch this film on
HBO, and all streaming devices,

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:08.310
and channels, as well.

00:06:08.310 --> 00:06:12.710
So, without further ado, I'll
turn it over to you guys.

00:06:12.710 --> 00:06:14.910
RAHIEL TESFAMARIAM: Thank
you so much, Chelsea.

00:06:14.910 --> 00:06:17.300
This is a wonderful
opportunity for me

00:06:17.300 --> 00:06:21.270
because I first saw the film
when Sue Patel showed it

00:06:21.270 --> 00:06:23.750
to me at a private screening.

00:06:23.750 --> 00:06:25.280
We were in director's chairs.

00:06:25.280 --> 00:06:28.550
And, being in a
huge, empty room,

00:06:28.550 --> 00:06:31.580
just crying my way through
the whole entire film.

00:06:31.580 --> 00:06:35.090
And, at that time, there
was no clear direction

00:06:35.090 --> 00:06:36.680
about what was going to happen.

00:06:36.680 --> 00:06:38.200
There was no HBO deal.

00:06:38.200 --> 00:06:41.390
It had not yet been
screened at Sundance.

00:06:41.390 --> 00:06:44.190
We were having discussions
about using Urban Cusp

00:06:44.190 --> 00:06:45.830
platform to screen it.

00:06:45.830 --> 00:06:48.550
And it was a very
grassroots discussion.

00:06:48.550 --> 00:06:52.910
And now to kind of see what
has happened with this film,

00:06:52.910 --> 00:06:56.780
to see that it has
aired on HBO, to see

00:06:56.780 --> 00:07:01.170
that it is on the short
list of Oscar nominations--

00:07:01.170 --> 00:07:04.680
I don't know if you
all knew that-- it

00:07:04.680 --> 00:07:07.720
is such a powerful
testament to what

00:07:07.720 --> 00:07:11.310
can be done with very little
when there is a will, when

00:07:11.310 --> 00:07:13.890
there is a desire, when
there is a clear purpose,

00:07:13.890 --> 00:07:16.100
and absolutely
with the strength,

00:07:16.100 --> 00:07:19.380
and resilience, and tenacity
of Jordan's parents.

00:07:19.380 --> 00:07:22.790
So I want to just personally
thank them for the example

00:07:22.790 --> 00:07:24.980
that they have set
for so many people.

00:07:24.980 --> 00:07:27.080
I've traveled, actually,
all over with them

00:07:27.080 --> 00:07:30.920
in different capacities
from Aspen to Memphis.

00:07:30.920 --> 00:07:32.570
We've been all over the country.

00:07:32.570 --> 00:07:36.600
And every single time, they
have the whole room in tears.

00:07:36.600 --> 00:07:40.430
They have people
completely inspired, eager

00:07:40.430 --> 00:07:42.360
to figure out what's next.

00:07:42.360 --> 00:07:44.590
And I think that
they always leave you

00:07:44.590 --> 00:07:49.780
with a sense of if they can
do this, then I have no excuse

00:07:49.780 --> 00:07:52.685
because they just move
with absolute resolve

00:07:52.685 --> 00:07:53.690
and conviction.

00:07:53.690 --> 00:07:56.960
And I just want to thank you
for who you are and especially

00:07:56.960 --> 00:07:58.230
at this moment in time.

00:07:58.230 --> 00:08:01.190
So, speaking to the
one year anniversary

00:08:01.190 --> 00:08:04.820
of Sandy Hook, everything that's
happening in this country,

00:08:04.820 --> 00:08:07.220
the discussion that we're
having about gun laws,

00:08:07.220 --> 00:08:10.920
and the discussion that we're
having about police brutality,

00:08:10.920 --> 00:08:14.870
this is such a timely film in
the context of all of that.

00:08:14.870 --> 00:08:16.240
And this is-- sorry.

00:08:16.240 --> 00:08:19.610
I'm recovering from a cold-- but
this is particularly the work

00:08:19.610 --> 00:08:22.440
that you're doing in
terms of gun legislation.

00:08:22.440 --> 00:08:24.064
Can you speak to
that a little bit?

00:08:24.064 --> 00:08:24.730
LUCY MCBATH: Oh.

00:08:24.730 --> 00:08:26.460
Thank you so much.

00:08:26.460 --> 00:08:28.986
And, once again, thank
you so much for inviting

00:08:28.986 --> 00:08:30.110
us to be here this evening.

00:08:30.110 --> 00:08:32.299
We're so excited.

00:08:32.299 --> 00:08:34.470
Yes, definitely so.

00:08:34.470 --> 00:08:39.299
I stay extremely busy
running from state to state

00:08:39.299 --> 00:08:43.600
and testifying across the
country on the opposition

00:08:43.600 --> 00:08:47.300
of the expansion of all of
the gun laws in the country,

00:08:47.300 --> 00:08:50.020
talking to our legislators,
and talking to civic leaders,

00:08:50.020 --> 00:08:53.560
and talking to academia,
talking to other grassroots

00:08:53.560 --> 00:08:57.560
organizations trying
to begin building

00:08:57.560 --> 00:09:01.410
coalitions of other grassroots
organizations and individuals

00:09:01.410 --> 00:09:04.390
that are concerned about what's
happening in the country.

00:09:04.390 --> 00:09:06.470
Believe it or not--
of course, we already

00:09:06.470 --> 00:09:08.230
know that in the
urban communities,

00:09:08.230 --> 00:09:10.560
this violence has
always been going on.

00:09:10.560 --> 00:09:14.025
And there have already been
established gun grassroots,

00:09:14.025 --> 00:09:17.410
gun violence organizations
that have been doing the work.

00:09:17.410 --> 00:09:21.690
So now my job is, as a national
spokesperson for Everytown

00:09:21.690 --> 00:09:24.960
for gun safety and also their
faith and community outreach

00:09:24.960 --> 00:09:28.100
leader, I go into
these communities.

00:09:28.100 --> 00:09:32.780
And I try to graph them into the
national work of gun violence

00:09:32.780 --> 00:09:37.040
prevention-- also within the
faith community, as well.

00:09:37.040 --> 00:09:41.976
So, as we say, we've become
the accidental activists.

00:09:41.976 --> 00:09:43.350
Neither one of us
would ever have

00:09:43.350 --> 00:09:47.960
imagined that we would be doing
this work, called to this work.

00:09:47.960 --> 00:09:50.230
But it is so relevant
for the time.

00:09:50.230 --> 00:09:52.200
It's so sorely needed.

00:09:52.200 --> 00:09:54.480
And this is what we
spend our time doing

00:09:54.480 --> 00:09:59.250
trying to encourage and engage
individuals and organizations

00:09:59.250 --> 00:10:02.540
in gun violence prevention
in the faith community

00:10:02.540 --> 00:10:04.195
and diverse communities.

