00:38:45.140 --> 00:38:46.890
I have taught criminal law.

00:38:49.720 --> 00:38:55.910
So I think it's really
important-- for everybody--

00:38:55.910 --> 00:38:57.610
but I think,
particularly, for people

00:38:57.610 --> 00:39:00.680
who have the luxury
of maintaining

00:39:00.680 --> 00:39:05.590
this sort of delusion to stop
thinking about the police

00:39:05.590 --> 00:39:08.940
as being an organization,
an institution that

00:39:08.940 --> 00:39:12.100
is there to protect all people.

00:39:12.100 --> 00:39:16.220
So the whole concept
of policing was

00:39:16.220 --> 00:39:18.530
developed in the United States.

00:39:18.530 --> 00:39:21.090
Policing is not an
old institution.

00:39:21.090 --> 00:39:22.860
It's a fairly new institution.

00:39:22.860 --> 00:39:25.560
And American policing was
developed in the United States

00:39:25.560 --> 00:39:28.580
to protect the property
of moneyed white people

00:39:28.580 --> 00:39:31.860
at a time when black people
were considered property.

00:39:31.860 --> 00:39:34.030
So I think that one of
the things that's going on

00:39:34.030 --> 00:39:37.890
is, yes, that's what the
police are there for.

00:39:37.890 --> 00:39:40.220
Another thing that's
going on, as Ron

00:39:40.220 --> 00:39:44.870
said, we need special
prosecutors because the way

00:39:44.870 --> 00:39:48.710
that cases get closed is
that the police testify

00:39:48.710 --> 00:39:50.290
against criminal defendants.

00:39:50.290 --> 00:39:51.950
And, since the
police are the people

00:39:51.950 --> 00:39:54.450
who are out there
selectively enforcing

00:39:54.450 --> 00:39:56.920
laws and disproportionately
and aggressively

00:39:56.920 --> 00:40:00.170
policing working class
communities of color,

00:40:00.170 --> 00:40:08.110
that means that their entire
job description involves putting

00:40:08.110 --> 00:40:10.300
poor black people in jail.

00:40:10.300 --> 00:40:15.430
And so it becomes very
difficult for a prosecutor

00:40:15.430 --> 00:40:22.410
to sincerely, and earnestly,
and zealously prosecute

00:40:22.410 --> 00:40:23.860
a police officer.

00:40:23.860 --> 00:40:25.777
So I think that call
for special prosecutors

00:40:25.777 --> 00:40:26.610
is absolutely right.

00:40:26.610 --> 00:40:28.690
And I really want to
second what Lumumba said.

00:40:31.450 --> 00:40:34.490
I know that it's
almost become a running

00:40:34.490 --> 00:40:36.340
joke about jury service.

00:40:36.340 --> 00:40:40.070
But this is actually
an opportunity for you

00:40:40.070 --> 00:40:51.500
to go and truly serve your
community to be a peer,

00:40:51.500 --> 00:40:59.220
to render judgment, or to
refuse to punish someone,

00:40:59.220 --> 00:41:02.310
to hear all that
evidence, and to really

00:41:02.310 --> 00:41:08.220
act in the service of justice
because the law and justice are

00:41:08.220 --> 00:41:11.240
not related to each other.

00:41:11.240 --> 00:41:14.850
And I think that, especially
for people who have always

00:41:14.850 --> 00:41:17.990
had the privilege of believing
that the law and justice,

00:41:17.990 --> 00:41:23.120
that that's a Venn diagram that
has a real substantial overlap,

00:41:23.120 --> 00:41:25.620
it's time to shed that idea.

00:41:25.620 --> 00:41:27.880
It's time to really
acknowledge the reality

00:41:27.880 --> 00:41:31.340
of what is happening and what
has always been happening.

00:41:31.340 --> 00:41:33.620
I think it's a real
mistake to think

00:41:33.620 --> 00:41:36.820
that this is a system that
started out good and got

00:41:36.820 --> 00:41:39.100
corrupted or that this is
a system that, in some way,

00:41:39.100 --> 00:41:44.490
can be redeemed because
it has never been intended

00:41:44.490 --> 00:41:46.055
to serve all people equally.

00:41:49.230 --> 00:41:51.030
I think it's really
crucial, it's

00:41:51.030 --> 00:41:56.220
really critical for anyone
who has relative power

00:41:56.220 --> 00:41:59.670
to be really honest
with themselves

00:41:59.670 --> 00:42:02.270
and to be really
honest with whoever's

00:42:02.270 --> 00:42:04.780
proximate to you,
to your communities

00:42:04.780 --> 00:42:11.200
to work to dismantle the idea
that the law and justice,

00:42:11.200 --> 00:42:13.900
that any well-developed
concept of justice

00:42:13.900 --> 00:42:18.715
has really any relationship
to the American legal system.

00:42:21.500 --> 00:42:23.860
TORRENCE BOONE: On the topic
of special prosecutors,

00:42:23.860 --> 00:42:25.610
how does that happen?

00:42:25.610 --> 00:42:27.490
How are special
prosecutors appointed?

00:42:27.490 --> 00:42:31.682
What are the situations
that underpin that?

00:42:31.682 --> 00:42:33.640
MOIRA MELTZER-COHEN: I
mean, it usually happens

00:42:33.640 --> 00:42:36.510
when there's an
egregious abuse of power.

00:42:36.510 --> 00:42:40.670
But this actually isn't-- I'm
not sure I'm entirely qualified

00:42:40.670 --> 00:42:44.840
to answer that question as far
as the technical aspects of it.

00:42:44.840 --> 00:42:51.750
But I think the
central piece of why

00:42:51.750 --> 00:42:55.300
we need special prosecutors
is that the whole logic

00:42:55.300 --> 00:42:56.780
behind having a
special prosecutor

00:42:56.780 --> 00:42:59.740
is that whoever is
normally the prosecutor

00:42:59.740 --> 00:43:02.730
is too entrenched
in a system of power

00:43:02.730 --> 00:43:08.190
that has gone horribly wrong
and where that power has been

00:43:08.190 --> 00:43:12.640
so egregiously
abused that it's not

00:43:12.640 --> 00:43:19.310
possible to maintain
even the appearance

00:43:19.310 --> 00:43:21.115
of impartial justice.

00:43:24.154 --> 00:43:25.320
RON DAVIS: It's interesting.

00:43:25.320 --> 00:43:27.540
But when you say
who has the power?

00:43:27.540 --> 00:43:30.864
Actually, who has the power is
the governors of the states.

00:43:30.864 --> 00:43:32.780
You have to realize the
federal government was

00:43:32.780 --> 00:43:36.650
created by the 13 colonies.

00:43:36.650 --> 00:43:39.400
And they've taken back to power
from the federal government.

00:43:39.400 --> 00:43:42.690
So that's why you see, every
time there's a mass shooting,

00:43:42.690 --> 00:43:47.620
President Obama looks like
he's just swallowed an egg.

00:43:47.620 --> 00:43:50.300
Because every time
he puts out something

00:43:50.300 --> 00:43:55.484
to discourage shooters, even
in the no fly zone-- anything

00:43:55.484 --> 00:43:57.900
that he puts out that says,
well, if they're on the no fly

00:43:57.900 --> 00:44:00.060
list, then we should
make sure that they

00:44:00.060 --> 00:44:02.085
don't get a chance to get guns.

00:44:02.085 --> 00:44:03.460
And he shakes his
head because he

00:44:03.460 --> 00:44:05.376
knows if he tries to
pass it through Congress,

00:44:05.376 --> 00:44:08.570
and he tries to pass it through
the Senate, they won't pass it.

00:44:08.570 --> 00:44:11.700
But, see, when I say power,
the governor of Connecticut

00:44:11.700 --> 00:44:13.380
decided, you know what?

00:44:13.380 --> 00:44:17.060
If you come into Connecticut,
and you're on the no fly list,

00:44:17.060 --> 00:44:19.620
you cannot get a gun or
bring a gun in the state

00:44:19.620 --> 00:44:20.840
of Connecticut.

00:44:20.840 --> 00:44:23.450
So the governors do
have the power to do it.

00:44:23.450 --> 00:44:27.301
And he made an executive order
to be effective immediately.

00:44:27.301 --> 00:44:27.800
See?

00:44:27.800 --> 00:44:31.182
So the governors of each state
can actually take action.

00:44:31.182 --> 00:44:32.640
LUMUMBA AKINWOLE-BANDELE:
If I can,

00:44:32.640 --> 00:44:34.420
I want to give a
little history about,

00:44:34.420 --> 00:44:37.460
at least in New York,
the call for-- which

00:44:37.460 --> 00:44:40.090
was originally
independent prosecutors.

00:44:40.090 --> 00:44:43.930
In '95, many of us were
doing this work in response

00:44:43.930 --> 00:44:49.600
to the killing of Anthony Baez
who was murdered Christmas

00:44:49.600 --> 00:44:53.109
Day by Officer Francis Livoti.

00:44:53.109 --> 00:44:54.650
And we decided that
we needed to stop

00:44:54.650 --> 00:44:56.670
this pattern of
continuously trying

00:44:56.670 --> 00:45:00.120
to go to DAs to get
justice when we recognized

00:45:00.120 --> 00:45:03.320
for decades that this was a
pattern that was not happening.

00:45:03.320 --> 00:45:06.120
We recognized that there
was a significant conflict

00:45:06.120 --> 00:45:10.450
of interest that Mr. Davis
clearly explained that does not

00:45:10.450 --> 00:45:15.090
allow the prosecutors
to be objective

00:45:15.090 --> 00:45:16.910
in any way in terms
of investigation

00:45:16.910 --> 00:45:18.700
and certainly not prosecution.

00:45:18.700 --> 00:45:20.470
And so the call
from the community,

00:45:20.470 --> 00:45:22.480
particularly the
parents at that time,

00:45:22.480 --> 00:45:24.520
was for an
independent prosecutor

00:45:24.520 --> 00:45:26.802
that did not have any
attachment to the state.

00:45:26.802 --> 00:45:29.010
Now people have said, well,
what does that look like?

00:45:29.010 --> 00:45:31.950
Will, I mean, it hasn't
manifested itself

00:45:31.950 --> 00:45:35.160
in any real way other
than a state attorney

00:45:35.160 --> 00:45:36.140
general taking it over.

00:45:36.140 --> 00:45:38.670
And that's where the term
special prosecutor came in.

00:45:38.670 --> 00:45:41.000
And so, even with
the executive order

00:45:41.000 --> 00:45:45.180
that was passed here in New
York State earlier this year,

00:45:45.180 --> 00:45:49.140
that was done based
on decades of pushing.

00:45:49.140 --> 00:45:51.820
When people told us in
'95, that's impossible.

00:45:51.820 --> 00:45:53.340
That will never happen.

00:45:53.340 --> 00:45:56.410
People told us earlier this
year, told their parents

00:45:56.410 --> 00:45:59.202
the state attorney general and
the governor hate each other.

00:45:59.202 --> 00:46:00.660
There's no way in
the world they'll

00:46:00.660 --> 00:46:02.820
come to an agreement for
this to actually happen.

00:46:02.820 --> 00:46:06.456
But it wasn't until those
parents stood with people

00:46:06.456 --> 00:46:08.330
in the streets, stood
with elected officials,

00:46:08.330 --> 00:46:10.880
said this is not
even negotiable.

00:46:10.880 --> 00:46:12.890
It's going to happen,
that it actually happened.

00:46:12.890 --> 00:46:14.770
It's not perfect.

00:46:14.770 --> 00:46:16.670
In fact, the governor's
playing with words

00:46:16.670 --> 00:46:19.400
trying to make it sound
like it's temporary.

00:46:19.400 --> 00:46:22.540
But it's not exactly
what we want.

00:46:22.540 --> 00:46:25.824
But it is a step in
the right direction.

00:46:25.824 --> 00:46:27.740
MOIRA MELTZER-COHEN:
